  "body": "#### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version: master\r\nOS & Version: OSX\r\nCommit hash : a602ee90f2c28eadbca8cdc2e143825a4c24ab23\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\n\r\nNode 2 will receive node 1 message on its filter\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\n\r\nNode 2 never receives the message; however if a node posts to itself, the message is caught by the filter and properly received\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\n\r\nI am using go-ethereum as a library and code which is very similar to the one used by the whisper API in `whisper/whisperv5/api.go` in `Post()` and `Messages()`. I can provide code if required\r\n\r\nWhen a node posts to itself the message is picked up by the filter and received. It looks like the message is not propagated by the network between the 2 nodes.\r\n\r\nTrying to debug that issue I have a few questions:\r\n\r\n - Is there a restriction on whispering between light nodes ?\r\n - do I need to do more than registering the whisperv5 service using\r\n        `utils.RegisterShhService(n, &whisperv5.DefaultConfig)` ?\r\n- does the `node.Config` need to hold particular values? for instance can I change the `name` to any client identifier of my choice ?\r\n - do the \"other\" nodes on the network refuse to forward a message for which the PoW is below their min PoW ?\r\n\r\nAny pointer appreciated. Many thanks for your help\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
